commentText: Back in 2005-2006 when Craigslist was just starting to spread to other cities, I picked up gigs left and right - people were highballing you more than anything, because not too many workers knew about the site and there was a high demand for all kinds of labor. I - quite naively - thought this would keep up for at least a few years.   I still use the site these days, but no one can rely on it in the way you're describing here, especially in dense cities like NYC, LA, SF... if it's a general labor gig, you probably have under 10-20 minutes to respond before the job is taken, and even then, you're completing against dozens of people. Advertising your general services like you did is a complete waste of time when employers know they'll get hundreds of replies from desperate people. The number of people I've seen offering less than minimum wage for skilled labor is disgusting.

It's tough when its really cold and location really is everything; when it's warmer out its a lot more lenient but often times, getting prime location can mean a difference of hundreds of dollars. On upcoming days with less than optimal weather, he would also stake out the places with a sleeping bag, all this for a working window of only 4-5 hours to take on the lunchtime rush. On a good day, we'd get over 120 orders with yumpling garnering just as many, if not more. At end's shift we would timetimes trade food (why waste food LOL) and their dumplings and bowls score a minimum 4/5 every time. Always a good eat.

commentText: Hey Dr. Mike, I love the fact that you have such respect for your nurses. I'm currently in school on the road to my nursing degree. I do however wish that others in the medical community could be recognized with the same level of importance. I work as a housekeeper at a nursing home. Housekeeping and maintenance staff within a medical facility to me, is part of The medical community. The language and attitudes towards those of us who aren't on the "clinical" side is to say the least offencive and heartbreaking. Sadly I myself was told in the nicest way possible that my role is equal to that of a slave with pay. People tend to forget that germs, viruses, and any number of infections are all around us, and we who clean help to keep us all safe. How can we help to change these attitudes? How do you view the housekeeping and maintenance staff within your facility?

commentText: From somebody who's done this:  There is a difference between fear of failure and fear of homelessness.  When I got five mortgage payments behind, I was no longer focusing my creative energy on writing, I was losing sleep because I was about to lose my house.  For a novelist anyway, I think the idea of quitting your day job is really bad advice.  I have found it easier to be creative when I don't have to worry about where my next house payment is coming from.  I've written six novels, one of them while unemployed and "chasing my dream."  Lemme tell you - financial desperation does not improve your odds.  I can still produce 10,000 words a week just fine as somebody who gets a paycheck.  And my books still don't sell.  That problem is not solved by adding the anxiety of having no income.  .02 from somebody who tried it and lost.

commentText: The older you get, the harder it is to serve two masters. The pay becomes higher and harder to leave, and physical loss of energy is a reality. Doesn't mean it can't be done. Just be aware of some realities that it gets tougher, not easier as time goes on.  I've lived through corporate jobs with good money and striking out on my own, only to find myself crying in the middle of my living room because I didn't know how I'd pay the rent. It's easy to take for granted the things we have when we fantasize about something better. There is a financial reality we have to account for. Get a plan. Live below your means. Figure out a way to do both as long as you need to...it doesn't have to be "either/or" it can be "either/and." At least for a period of time. Keep at it. What you want to do is get the horse running alongside the stagecoach before you take a leap. It may not be easy, but it's possible. Good luck to all reading this...we are all listening to this message and reading comments because of the same dissatisfaction....

commentText: Ever since I was a little kid, I was told how we need to get a job, work your life away, and eventually retire. I watched as my dad went off to teach kids every day and then return, a very honorable individual who contributed to society by taking on the task of trying to educate and mold students to learn. My dad was definitely a great man, but something I always wondered as I listened to my family and society is what was the point of it all? I see people wasting away, miserable at these things we're supposed to want, where they brag about having these overly expensive things. Then one day, I looked at my family, looked at their mindset and realized how I wanted none of it. I didn't want to waste my life doing a job, I didn't want or care about those nice things, I didn't give a damn about money, where the only reasons I pursued a paycheck was because it was a means to have a roof over my head and food. I came to the realization that work is worthless, it'll do nothing in the end and that we as a species need to focus more on our time, not wasting it working for someone else.

commentText: My sweet dear first year pro--in my opinion, you are on the fast-track to big success.  Concentrate your efforts on getting the best continuing education you can afford and look for chances to move up to higher-scale salons as soon as you know you are good enough.  It's great that you have some negative thinking questioning your talent, because it is young women like you and like me 28 years ago that worry that they need to improve and thus do improve, while our competitors think they are good enough.  Let me also suggest that you learn how to be a "Thairapist."  I am not just a cosmetologist and master barber.  I also have certifications in hypnosis and NLP.  Clients come to me sometimes just to have me give them a relaxing, massaging shampoo, conditioning, and blowout just for the 30 minutes of thairapy I give them.  Oh, I make over 250K a year and have cut back to about 25-28 hours a week.

I just want you to know how proud I am of you and how far you've come. I look up to you as one of my role models as a stylist. Being a stylist isn't easy on top of being a YouTuber, but if you can do it, than I can find my ways as well. Thank You for your channel and logging your cosmetology journey! Seriously, it helps me out so much and I know that it encourages so many others.

commentText: A few issues with the video and here is my analysis of your video. One: PSLF can be a great ROI but yeah her degree is a bit of an issue especially costing 115k.  Two: you are wrong on how the bank would look at her loan for a home. The payment is the payment. So when the dti is calculated it's based on the monthly payment not the whole debt like you stated. Third: I agree with you she is saving incorrectly. PSLF is calculated by AGI for the payment and this is done yearly. So she should be using the states retirement 401 k system tax deferred also using an HSA with HDHP. This creates less taxable income for the feds and the state of NY to grab at. Also could reduce he loan payment and allow her to stash cash during her 20's. Her current method is not to her advantage. Lastly, I do agree she needs to look at a home buying especially in NY where prices are dropping due to the SALT issue. Ok video but need to work on a few of the points. You did do some research but it's YouTube so you will have us sharpshooters.

commentText: Great video! 40 times the rent is your annual income. Also, random fact, annual income can be calculated by multiplying your hourly rate by 2080 (assuming you work full time or 40 hours per week).
